{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14123"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14123"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.01,0.11,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115595"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6803"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"2030"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"9488"},{"type":"tags","id":"11475"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32889"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48568"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of left-sided weakness and numbness. She reports significant work-related stress over the past month. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears anxious but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals left-sided weakness and sensory loss that does not correspond to known neuroanatomical patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nerve conduction studies and electromyography","Full blood count, electrolytes, and inflammatory markers","Lumbar puncture","MRI brain and cervical spine","Psychological assessment and cognitive testing"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of conversion disorder, also known as functional neurological symptom disorder. However, it is crucial to remember that conversion disorder is a diagnosis of exclusion, and organic causes must be ruled out before making this diagnosis. It is important to note that sensory examination findings are often somewhat inconsistent and difficult to replicate reliably, even in patients with organic neurological conditions, and therefore need to be interpreted with caution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood count, electrolytes, and inflammatory markers\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. These basic blood tests can help identify metabolic disturbances, electrolyte imbalances, or inflammatory conditions that may present with neurological symptoms. Inflammatory markers such as erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and C-reactive protein (CRP) can help screen for autoimmune or inflammatory disorders that can manifest with neurological presentations, including multiple sclerosis, systemic lupus erythematosus, or vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain and cervical spine\u003C/strong\u003E would be an important investigation to rule out structural lesions such as stroke, demyelination, or spinal cord pathology. While this would typically be performed early in the workup of focal neurological deficits, basic blood tests are often obtained first as they are readily available and can quickly identify reversible causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies and electromyography\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if peripheral neuropathy or neuromuscular junction disorders were suspected, but they are not the most appropriate initial investigation given the patient\u0027s presentation of hemisensory and motor symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there was suspicion of central nervous system infection, inflammation, or demyelinating disease. However, there are no features suggesting meningitis or encephalitis in this presentation, making it less appropriate as an initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychological assessment and cognitive testing\u003C/strong\u003E are important components in diagnosing conversion disorder, but they should not precede necessary medical investigations to rule out organic causes. A thorough psychological evaluation would be appropriate only after organic pathology has been excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter conducting appropriate investigations including blood tests and neuroimaging, and if no organic cause is identified, a comprehensive psychological assessment would be warranted. The diagnosis of conversion disorder should be based on positive clinical findings that are incompatible with recognised neurological conditions, rather than solely on the absence of an explanation for the symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conversion disorder diagnosis requires exclusion of organic causes through appropriate investigations.","Basic blood tests including inflammatory markers can help identify systemic conditions that may present with neurological symptoms.","Neuroimaging is essential to rule out structural lesions in patients presenting with focal neurological deficits."],"references":["Boland R, Verdiun M, Ruiz P. Kaplan \u0026 Sadock\u0027s synopsis of psychiatry. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2021 Feb 9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14123"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T15:13:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T15:26:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6803"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headi